Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[CCHF virus is endemic in Pakistan. Cases of CCHF occurred in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, 2 as recently as 12 Sep 2015 and now up to 11, and in Sindh provinces this year (2015) as well as in various parts of Pakistan last year (2014). With significant recent livestock movements into urban areas in preparation of the feast celebrating the Eid, there has been a significant risk of infection for those involved in slaughtering the animals and others in contact with the bodily fluids of those animals. Health care workers attending CCHF patients also need to be aware of their risk of infection in coming into contact with blood. However, there is no indication of how these reported cases became exposed to the CCHF virus.

The virus can cause severe viral hemorrhagic fever outbreaks, with a case fatality rate of 10-40 percent. The virus is transmitted by _Hyalomma_ spp. ticks or through contact with infected human blood or animal blood and tissues during and immediately after slaughter. The majority of cases have occurred in people involved in the livestock industry, such as agricultural workers, slaughterhouse workers, and veterinarians. Exposure in health care facilities can also occur.

The length of the incubation period depends on the mode of acquisition of the virus. Following infection by a tick bite, the incubation period is usually 1-3 days, with a maximum of 9 days.

CCHF virus is a tickborne virus in the genus _Nairovirus_, family _Bunyaviridae_.

A map of the provinces of Pakistan can be accessed at http://www.mapsofworld.com/pakistan/pakistan-political-map.html and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3728399,19537. - Mod.TY]
